<DOC><DOCNO> WSJ870825-0140 </DOCNO><HL> China Posts a Trade Surplus</HL><DD> 08/25/87</DD><SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO><IN> FRESTMONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON) </IN><DATELINE> BEIJING  </DATELINE><TEXT>   China posted a trade surplus of $5.20 billion for 1987's first seven months, in contrast to a year-earlier deficit of $1.68 billion, the official Xinhua agency quoted the Foreign Economic Relations and Trade Ministry as saying.    Exports increased 35% from the year before, to $20.2 billion, while imports declined 9.7%, to $15 billion.    Last year, according to ministry figures, Chinese trade was in deficit by $5.7 billion. In the past several years, the nation has imposed strict controls on imports to aid domestic industry and to help build up foreign-exchange reserves.    China's main export items are textiles and oil. </TEXT></DOC>